Thank you.

62
00:09:14,311 --> 00:09:19,135
So I'll just go through what was in the report, and I'll give a brief synopsis.

63
00:09:19,736 --> 00:09:24,580
And I can pull out some of the numbers that I may think are relevant.

64
00:09:24,901 --> 00:09:28,464
And you guys can ask me for other numbers that you want to see or whatever.

65
00:09:28,864 --> 00:09:29,465
We can go from there.

66
00:09:31,126 --> 00:09:38,918
Basically, what the report includes is everything that you asked for, a total cost, which includes a breakdown.

67
00:09:38,978 --> 00:09:46,190
The total cost includes the OT, the regular hours worked, the amount that we paid contractors.

68
00:09:46,844 --> 00:09:48,665
in the amount we bought for salt.

69
00:09:49,846 --> 00:09:51,587
So those are the major cost items.

70
00:09:51,868 --> 00:09:53,549
There are others, but those are the major ones.

71
00:09:54,329 --> 00:10:09,340
And then we also provided the commercial contract rates as well as non-commercial contract rates, provided a breakdown of departments and divisions for storm overtime and storm regular pay.

72
00:10:10,122 --> 00:10:15,126
We provided a list of the contractors and how much we paid each contractor.

73
00:10:15,887 --> 00:10:26,356
And we provided a snow equipment dispatch list, which are the 55 or so pieces that the city deploys.

74
00:10:26,996 --> 00:10:27,877
And then I provided

75
00:10:30,968 --> 00:10:36,810
two invoices for SALT that we used during that particular event.

76
00:10:37,870 --> 00:10:41,252
So that's the information that I provided.

77
00:10:41,272 --> 00:10:46,834
And then there was a request for some narrative in regards to challenges.

78
00:10:47,554 --> 00:10:52,215
So I'll just talk about that a little bit, and then we can kind of go where you guys want to go.

79
00:10:53,036 --> 00:10:55,817
The first question was about operational challenges.

80
00:10:57,285 --> 00:10:59,626
And actually, that was really the only question.

81
00:11:00,807 --> 00:11:03,628
So anyway, I provided an answer to that question.

82
00:11:03,688 --> 00:11:11,612
Really, the operational challenges this year included a relatively low availability of plows just in the region in general.

83
00:11:12,292 --> 00:11:13,913
We typically have between 30 and 40.

84
00:11:14,433 --> 00:11:17,574
Previous years, we've had up to 50 contractors or more.

85
00:11:18,015 --> 00:11:20,476
This January 2026 storm, we had 24.

86
00:11:20,596 --> 00:11:35,683
We don't have a definitive reason as to why, but the major speculation really is amongst folks like myself in Massachusetts is that we had a couple of winters with almost no plowing needed, and that really resulted in less folks available to provide that service.

87
00:11:37,579 --> 00:11:40,040
We even had some different things this year because we anticipated this.

88
00:11:40,320 --> 00:11:47,121
So we initiated an effort to get contractors on board early with an early sign-up bonus.

89
00:11:49,702 --> 00:11:51,583
We did get a few to sign up early, so that was good.

90
00:11:52,143 --> 00:11:56,864
We also advertised on our trucks this year, which we don't normally do, to see if we could get a few extra phone calls.

91
00:11:57,924 --> 00:11:58,824
I'm not sure if that worked.

92
00:11:59,125 --> 00:11:59,465
It may have.

93
00:12:01,207 --> 00:12:08,774
We also had a, we have two sidewalk machines, one of them broke down during this storm, and it was a long repair.

94
00:12:09,215 --> 00:12:11,697
So that set us back as far as sidewalk clearing.

95
00:12:12,598 --> 00:12:18,524
So that's another operational challenge that particular machine is folks know as Luke side Walker.

96
00:12:19,485 --> 00:12:26,355
is close to retirement, so we're looking at the end of life actually for that particular machine, and we're looking to replace it.

97
00:12:26,676 --> 00:12:32,826
So it will become a backup until it breaks down forever, but we will keep it in good repair and buy a new one to replace it.

98
00:12:33,226 --> 00:12:33,827
That is the plan.

99
00:12:34,864 --> 00:12:36,144
a better one, actually, to replace it.

100
00:12:37,125 --> 00:12:38,385
So that was another one.

101
00:12:38,785 --> 00:12:45,187
And then, of course, the obvious challenge was the amount of snow that fell and then the lack of thaw afterwards.

102
00:12:45,487 --> 00:12:47,788
It was really an anomaly.

103
00:12:47,828 --> 00:12:49,128
That storm was an anomaly.

104
00:12:49,208 --> 00:12:52,449
Typically, when you get a large amount of snow, there's typically a thaw after the storm.

105
00:12:53,329 --> 00:13:01,472
There was no thaw after the storm, so we had to deal with every single snowflake that had fallen for weeks thereafter, which is not typical.

106
00:13:04,343 --> 00:13:07,884
And then we did have some new employees and we had some new contractors.

107
00:13:08,104 --> 00:13:15,386
So that's always a challenge with every storm is making sure that the new employees know protocols and new contractors know where they're going and know what to do.

108
00:13:17,407 --> 00:13:24,628
Some next steps and recommendations that I included is to support the CIP.

109
00:13:24,709 --> 00:13:27,169
We have two snow removal pieces on there.

110
00:13:27,329 --> 00:13:28,830
One of them has been pushed back.

111
00:13:30,590 --> 00:13:38,676
But for a few years, and it's really just because we haven't really received much snow, I'd like to get a snowblower loader attachment.

112
00:13:38,817 --> 00:13:40,858
It's a very large snowblower that goes on a loader.

113
00:13:42,239 --> 00:13:47,704
The problem with that piece of equipment, you end up using it maybe a couple of times a year if you get some big storms.

114
00:13:48,084 --> 00:13:49,285
You don't use it for small storms.

115
00:13:49,825 --> 00:13:55,570
So it's a piece of equipment, hydraulic equipment, that would sit in our yard for most of the year.

116
00:13:58,120 --> 00:14:02,341
So it's a large purchase to have in a place like Boston.

117
00:14:02,922 --> 00:14:07,443
If we were in Buffalo, we'd use it 12 times a year, and that would be much more worth it.

118
00:14:08,203 --> 00:14:11,264
But I think the demand is there.

119
00:14:12,345 --> 00:14:16,906
My workers want it, and it's on the capital plan.

120
00:14:17,386 --> 00:14:21,248
So I think that's something that we should look at very closely.

121
00:14:21,268 --> 00:14:24,829
And let's see.

122
00:14:26,550 --> 00:14:27,370
What else did I write in here?

123
00:14:29,055 --> 00:14:33,599
Oh yeah, and just this was a just so you guys realize you know what we do as part of the operation.

124
00:14:33,639 --> 00:14:42,325
So after major storms and fires and whatever major storms, we always debrief, we have lessons learned incorporate into operations.

125
00:14:42,886 --> 00:14:45,768
So the next storm, we get better basically.

126
00:14:46,088 --> 00:14:50,411
And this mostly revolves around route assignments and communication between

127
00:14:51,873 --> 00:14:58,058
Foreman and operators, but other things are discussed to equipment failures at whatever.

128
00:14:58,779 --> 00:15:05,665
And a good example of this and I put this in my report is in our January storm.

129
00:15:07,153 --> 00:15:10,194
We did not have detailed mapping for route assignments.

130
00:15:10,374 --> 00:15:11,975
We've never had detailed mapping for route assignments.

131
00:15:12,415 --> 00:15:20,859
But after this January storm, we actually created route assignment maps with detailed route assignments on them through our GIS department.

132
00:15:22,000 --> 00:15:24,281
So we have that now, which we've never had before.

133
00:15:24,341 --> 00:15:26,022
And we used those during the February storm.

134
00:15:26,082 --> 00:15:30,263
And everybody seemed to think that they helped out with assignments.

135
00:15:30,544 --> 00:15:31,724
So that was a positive.

136
00:15:35,075 --> 00:15:35,335
Let's see.

137
00:15:35,355 --> 00:15:35,575
Yeah.

138
00:15:35,715 --> 00:15:45,041
So anyway, so that all that information I gave you, and then that information just in regards to the narrative and wherever you guys would like to take it, I'm on board.

139
00:15:46,165 --> 00:15:46,385
Great.

140
00:15:46,465 --> 00:15:53,512
Before I call on my fellow counselors, let me just, um, if I may, I'm curious, cause I can't find that report.

141
00:15:53,632 --> 00:15:58,056
And so I don't know whether you or, um, I don't, I don't see it at all.

142
00:15:58,696 --> 00:16:04,822
Or if the clerk can, cause it's, it's really helpful if we can actually review the report itself.

143
00:16:05,142 --> 00:16:09,226
So, um, between you and the clerk, could you have any idea of like where

144
00:16:11,061 --> 00:16:12,943
Is it under something that is not searchable?

145
00:16:13,203 --> 00:16:14,084
Is it listed?

146
00:16:14,244 --> 00:16:15,965
What's the title of the email?

147
00:16:16,005 --> 00:16:16,946
What date did it come?

148
00:16:18,007 --> 00:16:21,570
So I don't send council resolution responses directly to the city council.

149
00:16:21,610 --> 00:16:22,911
I send them to the mayor's office.

150
00:16:23,471 --> 00:16:27,134
And this one I believe had multiple departments on the request.

151
00:16:27,174 --> 00:16:29,156
So I'm not sure the status of those reports.

152
00:16:30,117 --> 00:16:36,742
So the protocol is that the mayor's office will respond to the council resolution.

153
00:16:38,011 --> 00:16:39,396
Okay, great.

154
00:16:39,596 --> 00:16:41,041
I will now go to my fellow councilors.

155
00:16:41,081 --> 00:16:43,028
Let me call on Councilor Lozaro.

156
00:16:45,733 --> 00:16:46,293
Thank you.

157
00:16:46,833 --> 00:16:49,495
I have a question that's very specific.

158
00:16:49,695 --> 00:16:54,117
I would, if this is in the report, I apologize.

159
00:16:55,557 --> 00:17:07,102
There's a section of Salem Street along the Salem Street burial ground that wasn't shoveled or plowed at all during any of the storms.

160
00:17:07,522 --> 00:17:12,364
And I have noticed it over and over again, and I've actually spoken to a,

161
00:17:17,001 --> 00:17:29,277
Andrew from the Chamber of Commerce who, you know, is with the Chevalier because they've had patrons that have complained about that stretch of sidewalk.

162
00:17:29,297 --> 00:17:32,381
There's parking over there and then people walk on the sidewalk.

163
00:17:33,002 --> 00:17:34,984
but when it's not plowed it gets really icy.

164
00:17:35,004 --> 00:17:36,525
It can be really dangerous.

165
00:17:36,825 --> 00:17:47,273
I can't think of who else would be in charge of that stretch of sidewalk and I was wondering if you could speak to why that might not have been plowed or if that is part of the plan for the future.

166
00:17:49,594 --> 00:17:53,757
Just I think that's an important, it's a really high traffic area in Medford Square.

167
00:17:54,598 --> 00:17:56,920
Salem Street that's leading right into where the

168
00:17:57,843 --> 00:18:02,248
bars and restaurants, the Chevalier, pretty much, you know, doctor's offices.

169
00:18:02,308 --> 00:18:03,329
It's right by City Hall.

170
00:18:04,670 --> 00:18:08,555
There's a lot of, there's just a lot of reasons why we would want to maybe make that safer.

171
00:18:08,595 --> 00:18:10,517
It's close to the senior center.

172
00:18:11,458 --> 00:18:17,284
So, you know, I know that the one side of it is a cemetery, but the parking is right there next to it.

173
00:18:17,324 --> 00:18:19,587
So just wanted to ask about that specifically.

174
00:18:20,273 --> 00:18:23,635
Sure, yeah, that's our purview, so we should be clearing that.

175
00:18:24,015 --> 00:18:25,476
It's low priority, I will say.

176
00:18:27,276 --> 00:18:33,219
And I don't have an explanation as to why, besides there was some issue that I don't know about.

177
00:18:33,700 --> 00:18:38,962
I believe the Riverside side was done, because I remember seeing that.

178
00:18:39,262 --> 00:18:40,683
So I think I'm just speculating here.

179
00:18:40,703 --> 00:18:41,323
I don't really know.

180
00:18:41,743 --> 00:18:47,326
But the assignment is to do those sidewalks, and the route includes those sidewalks, the brick one on Salem Street as well.

181
00:18:49,242 --> 00:18:50,203
Don't think it's getting done.

182
00:18:50,243 --> 00:18:53,227
I think they're doing one side and I'm not sure if they're doing river as well.

183
00:18:53,628 --> 00:18:57,432
So I think it may have been you or someone else brought this up.

184
00:18:58,233 --> 00:19:01,858
And this is another correction that we're doing.

185
00:19:01,898 --> 00:19:05,643
So we have a sidewalk list that's on paper.

186
00:19:06,083 --> 00:19:09,225
of what we're supposed to do, just written out in text.

187
00:19:10,006 --> 00:19:12,628
So that is, they may actually be done with it by now.

188
00:19:12,968 --> 00:19:21,094
But for next winter, the plan is to have a full sidewalk scope map, similar to our route assignments.

189
00:19:21,554 --> 00:19:26,978
It's just a more complicated map to draw because of the different limits of all the sidewalks that we do.

190
00:19:27,578 --> 00:19:32,361
But in general, the rule of thumb is that whoever is in control of the parcel

191
00:19:33,442 --> 00:19:34,563
should be clearing the sidewalks.

192
00:19:34,703 --> 00:19:36,244
So that's a city controlled parcel.

193
00:19:37,224 --> 00:19:41,847
It's owned by the city of Medford, and it just happens to be a historic parcel.

194
00:19:42,387 --> 00:19:42,727
Totally.

195
00:19:42,787 --> 00:19:57,655
I think that what happens is a lot of the time in situations like that when it's, I mean, the default being that people who own, it's either the businesses or the residents who live there need to clear their sidewalks.

196
00:19:57,715 --> 00:20:00,376
And then that one just, it's like, well, it's a graveyard.

197
00:20:00,396 --> 00:20:00,797
I mean,

198
00:20:01,917 --> 00:20:03,559
Obviously, yeah, it's the city, of course.

199
00:20:03,979 --> 00:20:12,886
So, but, and because it's not, you know, there's access to the cemetery, of course, but it's not about access to the cemeteries, but access to everything around it.

200
00:20:13,286 --> 00:20:16,789
And if your car is parked there, and also just the other thing being,

201
00:20:18,410 --> 00:20:27,523
access for people getting to the doctor's office, accessibility generally to the square, I just think it needs to be not low priority.

202
00:20:27,923 --> 00:20:33,111
And if there's any way, any process for adjusting that, I think it should be adjusted.

203
00:20:33,930 --> 00:20:38,491
What I mean by that is in comparison to basically first responder type stuff.

204
00:20:38,571 --> 00:20:41,191
So we have a hierarchy.

205
00:20:41,831 --> 00:20:46,632
The first thing on the hierarchy list is during storm, keep roads clear for emergency vehicles.

206
00:20:47,092 --> 00:20:47,713
That's number one.

207
00:20:48,113 --> 00:20:51,533
Number two is keep roads clear after the storm for emergency vehicles and cleanup.

208
00:20:52,093 --> 00:20:58,895
And then we start getting into things like parking lots for schools, parking lots for public buildings, and sidewalks is in there too.

209
00:20:59,895 --> 00:21:00,875
And then sidewalks,

210
00:21:01,695 --> 00:21:03,736
There's a hierarchy for sidewalks as well.

211
00:21:04,197 --> 00:21:12,501
So, it's nothing that you wouldn't want it so we do the sidewalk routes that are usually associated with the school and school bus stops.

212
00:21:13,262 --> 00:21:18,885
First, usually, and then we move on to city parcel parking lots and sidewalks.

213
00:21:19,305 --> 00:21:24,326
which tend to be the parks mostly, so all the sidewalks adjacent to parks, for example.

214
00:21:24,866 --> 00:21:28,987
Really, this parcel should fall into that category, like a park.

215
00:21:29,307 --> 00:21:29,947
Yeah, exactly.

216
00:21:30,127 --> 00:21:33,008
I wasn't trying to say that it's not a priority.

217
00:21:33,308 --> 00:21:42,870
What I'm saying is that on our hierarchy, that's the better word, is hierarchy of snow clearing, it should be down with sidewalks along parks.

218
00:21:43,390 --> 00:21:44,791
And it it fell through the cracks.

219
00:21:44,851 --> 00:21:46,891
It wasn't supposed to never have been cleared.

220
00:21:46,991 --> 00:21:48,832
But what happened was it never got cleared.

221
00:21:49,012 --> 00:21:50,193
It became impacted.

222
00:21:50,293 --> 00:21:51,073
It became ice.

223
00:21:51,253 --> 00:22:03,958
And then people who park near there and walk to a restaurant and then patronize the businesses in Medford are walking in the street on one of the most dangerous streets that we have where people drive really fast and they're like.

224
00:22:04,918 --> 00:22:21,482
all kinds of people of all walks of life walking in the street trying not to get hit by cars in the dark in the winter or they're slipping on the sidewalk so it shouldn't have happened and I think they like it's whatever it was a mistake but it should be you know prioritized in the future and it happened last year too you know like it happens all the time

225
00:22:22,407 --> 00:22:23,328
Yeah, right, right, right.

226
00:22:23,348 --> 00:22:24,508
So I don't have a good explanation for it.

227
00:22:24,568 --> 00:22:27,110
So I think the best fix, I think, is what we're doing.

228
00:22:27,130 --> 00:22:31,553
Because I can say to those guys, oh, do this, do this a million times.

229
00:22:31,653 --> 00:22:38,237
But unless it is not just written down, but we show them, I'm hoping that just solves all these.

230
00:22:38,317 --> 00:22:40,258
It's not the only sidewalk that has been missed.

231
00:22:40,758 --> 00:22:46,721
When the sidewalk machine gets deployed to a location to clear a sidewalk, do they do all of the sidewalks?

232
00:22:46,981 --> 00:22:47,701
Not all the time.

233
00:22:47,821 --> 00:22:51,583
And then we're trying to chase it later on, and it gets compacted on ice.

234
00:22:51,643 --> 00:22:53,884
And then we're kind of like, well, now there's not a lot we can do.

235
00:22:54,385 --> 00:22:56,145
So hear you loud and clear.

236
00:22:56,265 --> 00:23:02,008
And hopefully the sidewalk map just changes this for good.

237
00:23:02,128 --> 00:23:04,049
So there's no excuses, basically.

238
00:23:04,529 --> 00:23:04,729
Great.

239
00:23:05,190 --> 00:23:05,510
Sounds good.

240
00:23:05,750 --> 00:23:06,070
Thank you.

241
00:23:07,891 --> 00:23:08,331
Thank you.

242
00:23:08,351 --> 00:23:10,032
I will call on Councilor Scarpelli.

243
00:23:12,875 --> 00:23:13,716
Thank you, Madam Chair.

244
00:23:14,796 --> 00:23:16,297
Tim, thanks for being here.

245
00:23:16,337 --> 00:23:19,798
I know it's not easy, but I, you know, and I agree with you.

246
00:23:19,878 --> 00:23:24,960
I think the last storm, the first storm was difficult and it was an anomaly.

247
00:23:25,141 --> 00:23:28,082
I mean, and me and you had a conversation.

248
00:23:28,142 --> 00:23:40,807
We talked about eliminating any of the rumors that were going around and understanding the process of why we had such low turnout for support.

249
00:23:42,750 --> 00:24:01,121
I know that, just to be clear with everybody, talked to Tim and had conversations with some former contractors who stated that the process that's now implemented is too daunting for them, was told that the

250
00:24:04,783 --> 00:24:16,253
that the new contractors now would need a separate insurance binder for liability, and talked with Tim.

251
00:24:16,294 --> 00:24:21,558
Tim dispelled those rumors to make sure that's not the case.

252
00:24:23,180 --> 00:24:27,864
But I've spent a lot of time with your team during the storm, actually.

253
00:24:30,040 --> 00:24:31,921
Um, see how hard they've worked.

254
00:24:32,202 --> 00:24:35,064
I want to first publicly again commend them.

255
00:24:35,084 --> 00:24:39,447
Um, the team with boots on the ground were amazing.

256
00:24:40,127 --> 00:24:50,234
They went above and beyond considering the lack of equipment, lack of, um, contractual support and the low number of DPW employees.

257
00:24:50,254 --> 00:24:50,835
That's nothing.

258
00:24:50,855 --> 00:24:51,275
That's not.

259
00:24:51,675 --> 00:24:52,476
That's nothing new.

260
00:24:52,616 --> 00:24:55,718
So I appreciate everybody doing their due diligence.

261
00:24:55,878 --> 00:24:56,158
So, um,

262
00:24:57,976 --> 00:25:03,928
But I think that there are some glaring questions that we need to correct as we move forward.

263
00:25:05,596 --> 00:25:09,479
I'm not going to talk about what corner hasn't been done or what has been done.

264
00:25:09,499 --> 00:25:17,024
I think that's something that should be done over an email so we can document and understand with the gaps that we've had.

265
00:25:17,124 --> 00:25:31,393
But I'm a little confused because as of, I think, last year and the year before, when I've been involved with talking with your team and everything and talking with contractors, you said that the routes have never been mapped.

266
00:25:32,113 --> 00:25:33,154
They've always been mapped.

267
00:25:33,414 --> 00:25:46,585
I think I can pull up some of the roots that were shared with me maybe last year or the year before, just to understand who I needed a contact when I was getting phone calls.

268
00:25:46,665 --> 00:25:51,388
And like I said, this first storm, I received 54 phone calls and emails.

269
00:25:51,428 --> 00:25:52,830
So we broke a record.

270
00:25:52,990 --> 00:25:57,894
And as we went forward with that, I started talking and listening.

271
00:26:02,800 --> 00:26:06,902
I found some issues that really were a little confusing and bothersome to me.

272
00:26:09,985 --> 00:26:19,892
The contractors, we know that we have to get to understanding, were people informed, staff informed, were they giving their roots or not?

273
00:26:20,953 --> 00:26:22,714
Because that's something new, what you said today.

274
00:26:23,655 --> 00:26:26,777
Second, understanding the contractor's numbers that are low,

275
00:26:28,012 --> 00:26:36,977
can you provide us with any processes used to train these contractors?

276
00:26:37,417 --> 00:26:40,659
Because I think that was, like you said, one of the concerns.

277
00:26:40,759 --> 00:26:53,046
And even with some of the newer DPW employees that were in a plot for the first time possibly, that were they trained in any way in going through the process?

278
00:26:54,227 --> 00:26:55,688
I'm very familiar with this because

279
00:26:56,328 --> 00:27:02,713
I'm part of my snow removal team and snow prepared team in my municipality that I work with.

280
00:27:03,774 --> 00:27:13,541
I'd like to ask also, if you can, when I'm done with this list, is do we do a pre-storm prep meeting?

281
00:27:14,622 --> 00:27:15,443
We do that in

282
00:27:16,563 --> 00:27:26,810
In Somerville, we talk with everybody involved, and we know exactly what's going on, who's going where, what's going to happen, and who's going to support that.

283
00:27:26,870 --> 00:27:29,451
I think that's important, that if we're doing that.

284
00:27:31,252 --> 00:27:36,856
One of the biggest things, Tim, that, you know, I know that this isn't anything that you need to worry about.

285
00:27:36,876 --> 00:27:43,960
I was hoping someone from the mayor's office, maybe you can share this with the mayor's office, but we have a pretty

286
00:27:44,640 --> 00:27:46,081
robust communication team.

287
00:27:46,381 --> 00:27:52,065
And the communication before and the communication after the storms were horrible.

288
00:27:52,105 --> 00:28:05,693
That's probably one of the biggest concerns and issues and reasons why we had such negative feedback publicly, through social media, personally with phone calls and emails, is that people really weren't informed.

289
00:28:07,234 --> 00:28:09,215
You know, the business district really suffered.

290
00:28:09,295 --> 00:28:13,338
We heard a lot about their issues where they weren't, they didn't know what was going on.

291
00:28:13,978 --> 00:28:17,181
And again, like I said, I don't, this isn't on you, Tim.

292
00:28:17,221 --> 00:28:20,963
I think that we need more of a comprehensive plan with the whole team.

293
00:28:21,704 --> 00:28:24,446
And I don't think we see that.

294
00:28:24,466 --> 00:28:33,552
I will be honest with you, in my profession where we are, we have a group of 60 people and the communications team is on the forefront of that.

295
00:28:34,209 --> 00:28:53,919
because they're listening and they're relaying everything that's discussed in the pre-storm meeting to be shared with the community so we know everything from when the cars have to be off the streets and when the parking is lifted plus the process of how we're going to eliminate snow if needed or so on and so forth.

296
00:28:53,959 --> 00:28:55,120
We can get deeper into that.

297
00:28:58,581 --> 00:29:02,984
One thing I've realized that I've heard and I just need to know this,

298
00:29:04,745 --> 00:29:09,731
And again, I don't want to be critical with you because I think you're being your hands are being tied.

299
00:29:09,751 --> 00:29:13,476
And you can maybe clarify this during the storms.

300
00:29:14,297 --> 00:29:19,023
If it's outside of regular work hours, is our leadership team there?

301
00:29:19,183 --> 00:29:19,924
Are you there?

302
00:29:20,084 --> 00:29:21,686
Is our assistant there present?

303
00:29:23,515 --> 00:29:25,216
Because I think that's important also.

304
00:29:25,236 --> 00:29:33,463
I talked to some of my friends and teammates in my community, and they were saying that's one of the issues that Medford has.

305
00:29:34,123 --> 00:29:39,547
And I said, I don't know where they heard that from, but I said, I want to make sure that's another rumor.

306
00:29:40,108 --> 00:29:42,670
Because I think that, you know, when we talk about

307
00:29:43,330 --> 00:30:00,361
You know, I was in the process with the prior mayor when we had a DPW director come on, and one of the biggest issues why the person that they wanted didn't accept the job is because the administration at the time wouldn't allow either comp time or flex time or overtime.

308
00:30:01,655 --> 00:30:20,569
during during snow storms or after snow storms or after they've worked past their 40 hours because i think that's important that we have to know if that is the case because that has to be corrected again that's not your fault tim if that's the case but i want to make sure that's identified um and then i think as we move forward i think we're really it'd be

309
00:30:21,510 --> 00:30:45,387
it would help this councilor understand that what training is done and you know what reports are done before and after so whatever we can do when it comes to budget time that when you know I hear you with the big snow blower and even if it's one storm if it helps us make our streets safe and our sidewalks safe

310
00:30:46,147 --> 00:30:53,891
If it's something that we can make work in the capital plan, I'm going to support a thousand percent, even if it's just one storm every two years.

311
00:30:53,911 --> 00:30:56,652
I think it's that important because we saw what happened.

312
00:30:56,672 --> 00:30:57,132
You weren't ready.

313
00:30:57,832 --> 00:30:59,313
Nobody was ready for the first storm.

314
00:30:59,493 --> 00:31:04,195
And I think that, to your credit, the second storm was drastically better.

315
00:31:04,295 --> 00:31:05,336
Everybody I thought that

316
00:31:05,956 --> 00:31:10,197
We really, you really pushed your team together and it really showed.

317
00:31:10,337 --> 00:31:14,478
I think the second storm that you didn't, you didn't hear anything.

318
00:31:14,498 --> 00:31:20,039
You didn't, we didn't, at least personally, I didn't entertain any negativity with anybody.

319
00:31:20,579 --> 00:31:26,840
Understanding that the team was out there working night and day and it got done in a better format.

320
00:31:26,860 --> 00:31:31,541
And I think that the last thing is, do we, do you have,

321
00:31:33,220 --> 00:31:59,247
um a process where you are in in communications with our state partners because as we know we have um a lot of state roads that intersect and and making sure that we're you know that you know because we have a lot of state roads that intersect so state will take care of one sidewalk then all of a sudden there'll be another sidewalk that's not being touched and i will tell you our two code enforcement officers

322
00:32:00,223 --> 00:32:21,993
did it i thought they were phenomenal they any any call i received they were out there sending me pitches with big orange tickets on people's doors so they really did their due diligence making sure that our streets our sidewalks were passable and safe for our pedestrians especially as seniors and our students as they walked to school and

323
00:32:22,873 --> 00:32:40,077
And then I know we also talked about this and I think that people have to also hear this publicly that, um, you know, what we're hearing that the city isn't plowing, um, private private roads anymore because, um, they're not part of the system.

324
00:32:40,117 --> 00:32:42,458
And I think that if that is the case,

325
00:32:43,278 --> 00:32:47,422
in places I think we need to know as the council and we need to prepare.

326
00:32:47,442 --> 00:33:04,315
I know that I've asked that and you've presented as well when it comes to getting more of a community meeting with people that reside in a private way and having them understand the protocol of what their responsibilities are now.

327
00:33:04,976 --> 00:33:07,718
I know that the mayor is moving forward with more of a

328
00:33:09,459 --> 00:33:14,782
detailed plan or rule of what can be done and can't be done on private ways.

329
00:33:14,842 --> 00:33:25,168
So I think that if if it was a mistake that some of these private ways just were missed or we're really not doing them, that'll be interesting to know as well.

330
00:33:25,208 --> 00:33:29,730
So I know that's a lot, Tim, and I appreciate you coming out and listening and responding.

331
00:33:29,770 --> 00:33:38,455
But I just wanted to make sure that I asked all these questions because these are the questions that were posted and presented to me during the storm.

332
00:33:38,495 --> 00:33:38,975
So thank you.

333
00:33:39,947 --> 00:33:43,473
And I will absolutely give Commissioner McGivern the opportunity to respond.

334
00:33:44,666 --> 00:33:45,386
All right, thank you very much.

335
00:33:46,307 --> 00:33:49,208
So I'll just go and order the contractor apps.

336
00:33:49,768 --> 00:33:50,909
That's the rumor.

337
00:33:50,989 --> 00:33:53,030
So we've been doing it the same way for about three years.

338
00:33:53,510 --> 00:33:57,952
So we have two applications, two ways to become a contractor with the city.

339
00:33:58,312 --> 00:34:04,876
One of them is the full legal way that it should be done, which is they have a full insurance rider.

340
00:34:05,216 --> 00:34:09,558
They are prepared to work in the public way with all the protections in place.

341
00:34:11,072 --> 00:34:12,753
that they get paid more money.

342
00:34:13,033 --> 00:34:21,096
And those are the larger landscaping companies typically or whatever, the larger plowing companies that have that corporate setup and they can do that.

343
00:34:21,616 --> 00:34:27,238
Then there's the guy or gal with a pickup truck and a plow blade.

344
00:34:27,939 --> 00:34:29,579
Usually they're just plowing for the city.

345
00:34:29,679 --> 00:34:31,440
They don't have general liability insurance.

346
00:34:31,460 --> 00:34:33,241
They don't have an LLC.

347
00:34:34,141 --> 00:34:35,642
They just want to plow and get paid.

348
00:34:36,975 --> 00:34:40,517
So that's, you know, we do still do that.

349
00:34:41,697 --> 00:34:42,377
It is an option.

350
00:34:42,517 --> 00:34:43,918
They don't get paid as much.

351
00:34:44,478 --> 00:34:46,379
And just, I'll tell you what the rates are.

352
00:34:49,620 --> 00:35:01,825
It's basically, if you have commercial, a commercial setup and you have the proper insurance, you're getting for that pickup truck, you're getting $110 an hour.

353
00:35:02,365 --> 00:35:04,866
But if you are just non-commercial,

354
00:35:05,750 --> 00:35:09,292
guy or gal with a pickup truck and a blade, you get $98 per hour.

355
00:35:09,752 --> 00:35:13,374
Those are competitive rates.

356
00:35:14,675 --> 00:35:18,837
And we encourage folks to get insurance because it protects everybody involved.

357
00:35:19,398 --> 00:35:24,300
I don't want to be in a situation, and neither do you folks, where a uninsured plow driver for the city

358
00:35:26,101 --> 00:35:27,082
hurt somebody badly.

359
00:35:28,023 --> 00:35:29,324
We don't want to be in that situation.

360
00:35:29,784 --> 00:35:32,406
So, you know, there's that.

361
00:35:32,426 --> 00:35:32,966
All right.

362
00:35:34,187 --> 00:35:34,808
Root foreman.

363
00:35:35,088 --> 00:35:35,308
Sure.

364
00:35:35,348 --> 00:35:37,189
We have a map and you've seen a map before.

365
00:35:37,430 --> 00:35:37,930
It's a map.

366
00:35:37,990 --> 00:35:39,231
It's a root foreman map.

367
00:35:39,731 --> 00:35:43,254
It's a map that tells the foreman what they're responsible for.

368
00:35:43,794 --> 00:35:50,759
But that map never has gotten into the granular as to, hey, these are the streets that we are obligated to plow.

369
00:35:51,660 --> 00:36:05,952
We had them generally on there, but now what we can hand out in 11 by 17s, we can hand out to the root foreman an 11 by 17 sheet that has all of their root streets on it that they can then make copies of and give to contractors.

370
00:36:07,173 --> 00:36:08,054
That's the difference.

371
00:36:08,394 --> 00:36:10,876
So sure, yeah, you did see a foreman map.

372
00:36:10,896 --> 00:36:13,959
So it's just an improvement to the system that already was in place.

373
00:36:14,439 --> 00:36:19,684
And the reason for that improvement, I could talk a little bit more about because the next item is training.

374
00:36:20,404 --> 00:36:24,205
So new drivers, new contractors, yes, they do need to be trained.

375
00:36:25,065 --> 00:36:32,308
Typically, the way we do that is that the route foreman or someone else who knows the route goes with them the first time.

376
00:36:32,988 --> 00:36:34,248
That's typically how it's done.

377
00:36:34,688 --> 00:36:42,771
If we have a new employee that has never done a route before, they will follow someone else who has done that route for the first time.

378
00:36:43,491 --> 00:36:44,891
And then the kinks are worked out.

379
00:36:45,932 --> 00:36:46,312
Typically,

380
00:36:46,992 --> 00:36:52,276
Before, so that's the training part and then that leads right into the pre storm prep meeting.

381
00:36:52,637 --> 00:36:54,638
So we do have a meeting before all of our storms.

382
00:36:56,199 --> 00:37:04,406
Sometimes they're up in my office this one was down in the yard, and the police always come, you know, or someone talks to the police but this meeting the police you know we're there.

383
00:37:05,386 --> 00:37:10,510
And we talked about all of the things that you brought up, Councilor Scarpelli, all the things that needed.

384
00:37:11,631 --> 00:37:18,716
So, so what everybody sees the only way that can happen is if we have a pre meeting, and it's, yeah, so that definitely does happen.

385
00:37:20,582 --> 00:37:27,843
You know, the comms piece of that is another set of meetings and another set of communications.

386
00:37:28,503 --> 00:37:37,005
So, you know, we're doing our operations preparation with the police and we're doing our equipment preparation and we're, you know, making sure we have enough salt.

387
00:37:37,245 --> 00:37:38,525
So we're doing all of those things.

388
00:37:38,965 --> 00:37:48,707
And at the same time, I'm also communicating with the department heads and the mayor, the chiefs, the comms director,

389
00:37:49,227 --> 00:37:55,089
everybody that would need to be involved in a snow storm emergency first responder type response.

390
00:37:56,629 --> 00:37:59,270
A lot of that is done over text message, group text message.

391
00:38:00,430 --> 00:38:04,411
We found, especially this last couple of years, it's a very effective way to do it.

392
00:38:04,771 --> 00:38:09,613
So we'll have an initial meeting, and then we all continue communication via a group text message.

393
00:38:11,393 --> 00:38:12,513
Seems to work out really well.

394
00:38:12,533 --> 00:38:13,274
I appreciate it.

395
00:38:15,030 --> 00:38:20,494
So I sign up actually for all of the notifications of our surrounding communities and other ones.

396
00:38:21,094 --> 00:38:24,276
So I know what they're putting up for communications on their systems.

397
00:38:25,697 --> 00:38:26,998
Medford's is comparable.

398
00:38:27,078 --> 00:38:28,719
Sometimes we give more information.

399
00:38:30,060 --> 00:38:33,702
We have a regular person giving the robo calls as opposed to a robot.

400
00:38:35,205 --> 00:38:43,211
And we tend to point folks in, I think, to the website in a better direction than just some of the other towns and cities.

401
00:38:43,851 --> 00:38:45,692
But everybody does it a little bit differently.

402
00:38:46,013 --> 00:38:48,594
So we can learn from what our neighbors do.

403
00:38:48,775 --> 00:38:50,216
So, you know, that's always there.

404
00:38:50,276 --> 00:38:52,297
And I agree, it's more of a comms thing.

405
00:38:52,657 --> 00:39:00,043
But I will tell you that that person in that department is involved, usually at the very beginning when we start talking about storm prep.

406
00:39:01,424 --> 00:39:08,831
And then what happens after that, you know, that really doesn't have anything to do with the DPW we're going to we're going to be our be the first responders and do our best.

407
00:39:09,412 --> 00:39:14,577
At that point, once we decide there's a snow emergency then that's we go into full emergency mode.

408
00:39:17,849 --> 00:39:18,770
So I think I addressed all those.

409
00:39:18,830 --> 00:39:19,550
Leadership presence.

410
00:39:20,051 --> 00:39:25,155
So me and the deputy, we don't get paid any overtime or salary.

411
00:39:25,835 --> 00:39:27,837
But it's either me or him.

412
00:39:27,957 --> 00:39:29,318
We do show up for the storms.

413
00:39:30,379 --> 00:39:31,520
If he's not going to go, I go.

414
00:39:32,140 --> 00:39:36,784
He actually has been plowing as well for the storms with approval from the unit.

415
00:39:37,224 --> 00:39:38,565
So I'm not doing any work at the unit.

416
00:39:38,846 --> 00:39:40,887
But for sure, he's there.

417
00:39:41,448 --> 00:39:43,970
And I think it was the February storm

418
00:39:44,670 --> 00:39:46,411
deputy wasn't available, Scott wasn't available.

419
00:39:46,791 --> 00:39:48,471
So I went in at the all in.

420
00:39:49,692 --> 00:39:55,754
And I don't know what rumors are going about, but I think we're different, actually, than other DPWs.

421
00:39:56,994 --> 00:39:58,775
The leadership does go in at storms.

422
00:39:59,415 --> 00:40:04,817
Sometimes it's just for morale, just so the workers can see our face, see my face.

423
00:40:05,957 --> 00:40:09,118
They joke around with me, why aren't you plowing, and stuff like that.

424
00:40:10,259 --> 00:40:12,620
And I'm not getting paid overtime like they are, right?

425
00:40:14,432 --> 00:40:19,115
I usually at that point want to get home and go see my kids.

426
00:40:19,135 --> 00:40:24,758
But getting the plow drivers out the door and seeing it happen is something that we do try to do.

427
00:40:26,601 --> 00:40:30,284
So then as far as communication with state partners go, yeah, we do that.

428
00:40:30,364 --> 00:40:33,367
We have to.

429
00:40:33,547 --> 00:40:34,488
We don't really have a choice.

430
00:40:34,508 --> 00:40:37,350
And I'll give you just a few examples.

431
00:40:37,470 --> 00:40:38,792
We coordinate with them on bridges.

432
00:40:39,012 --> 00:40:43,496
So obviously, we don't lift our plow blades up when we go over bridges.

433
00:40:43,916 --> 00:40:48,860
We also have to deal with underneath the bridges, sidewalks, and on top of bridges, sidewalks on top of bridges.

434
00:40:49,341 --> 00:40:51,723
So we're doing those.

435
00:40:52,003 --> 00:40:53,724
We're also doing the MBTA bus stops.

436
00:40:54,705 --> 00:41:00,651
That's usually kind of last, but we do do them even though personally I think the TV should do them but I agree.

437
00:41:01,131 --> 00:41:01,412
Whatever.

438
00:41:03,353 --> 00:41:07,457
But we do it and we also have to forward complaints to both.

439
00:41:08,499 --> 00:41:13,162
DOT, DCR, anybody else at the state is listening.

440
00:41:14,443 --> 00:41:15,003
Yeah.

441
00:41:15,043 --> 00:41:16,504
So, you know, that's constantly happening.

442
00:41:17,285 --> 00:41:23,629
DCR is the owners of a lot of the parks on the river, but we actually operate those parks.

443
00:41:24,189 --> 00:41:27,891
So, you know, you'd think that we'd have a lot of coordination with DCR.

444
00:41:27,911 --> 00:41:28,572
We don't have that much.

445
00:41:28,912 --> 00:41:32,835
It's usually MassDOT that we're coordinating with District 4.

446
00:41:34,652 --> 00:41:39,876
And then as far as private roads and driveways, so our policies, I know that there's a lot of, you know, chatter out there.

447
00:41:39,996 --> 00:41:41,617
So our policies have not changed.

448
00:41:42,378 --> 00:41:44,279
We plow all the public ways.

449
00:41:44,639 --> 00:41:46,681
We also plow all the private ways.

450
00:41:47,201 --> 00:41:49,723
Private ways are different from private driveways.

451
00:41:50,363 --> 00:41:53,386
Driveways are on building parcels.

452
00:41:54,046 --> 00:42:00,189
And they are privately owned, and people pay taxes on the land that they're on.

453
00:42:00,769 --> 00:42:06,071
Private ways are parcels of land that are right-of-ways that people don't pay taxes on.

454
00:42:06,571 --> 00:42:10,493
They're usually derelict, which just means that there's no clear title to them.

455
00:42:12,054 --> 00:42:15,255
The city does plow those in the interest of public safety.

456
00:42:16,055 --> 00:42:25,222
And it is kind of on that line of, is the city, is the public city using public resources to plow private property?

457
00:42:25,702 --> 00:42:28,884
We are, but we're doing it in the interest of public safety.

458
00:42:29,265 --> 00:42:35,029
Because the alternative in Medford, I don't think would be a good situation.

459
00:42:36,049 --> 00:42:42,093
If we were to ever not plow private ways, it would be a multi,

460
00:42:42,974 --> 00:42:49,497
year-long transition to get from point A to point B. I don't see that happening.

461
00:42:50,077 --> 00:42:53,479
I mean, there's a huge topic here to talk about.

462
00:42:53,699 --> 00:42:54,659
Yeah, I agree.

463
00:42:54,679 --> 00:42:56,140
I agree with you, yeah.

464
00:42:56,200 --> 00:42:57,801
But we don't need to delve into it, right?

465
00:42:57,841 --> 00:43:08,045
But as of right now, status quo, and I don't see this changing for any time soon, is the city plows public ways and private ways, but we don't never have plowed private driveways.

466
00:43:08,625 --> 00:43:10,406
Okay, that's perfect.

467
00:43:12,634 --> 00:43:12,794
Right.

468
00:43:13,174 --> 00:43:15,736
I think I got all your questions, Councillor Scott.

469
00:43:15,756 --> 00:43:16,396
No, that's right.

470
00:43:16,496 --> 00:43:23,539
For those people who don't know, if you don't lift your blade or going over a bridge, that's how you bury the people on the other side.

471
00:43:23,919 --> 00:43:28,722
I learned that because that was my first mistake when I was applying for DOT one year, so I got yelled at.

472
00:43:30,242 --> 00:43:36,384
When you go over a bridge, you're supposed to lift the blade.

473
00:43:36,404 --> 00:43:41,426
They have those expansion joints at either side, and they try to protect those.

474
00:43:41,906 --> 00:43:43,126
Well, I know.

475
00:43:43,226 --> 00:43:45,727
Tim, I appreciate it.

476
00:43:45,767 --> 00:43:48,128
Like I said, I think the team has to be commended.

477
00:43:48,188 --> 00:43:53,250
I think, especially from Storm 1, that was an anomaly to where we were the second storm.

478
00:43:54,993 --> 00:44:22,930
was drastically different and again like I said the clarification the communication you're right it's not you guys I think that um what the team has to what the city has to really what I want to see from the mayor's office is making sure that everybody's informed as much as possible with all the process so they they they're not having to call us to call DPW or and something that's very simple and I think that that's important I think that uh and and to be clear

479
00:44:24,365 --> 00:44:29,848
It was some of the employees in our neighboring community that said, hey, what are you guys doing?

480
00:44:29,868 --> 00:44:37,112
A, B, and C. These are just, you know, so that's why I wanted to share with you so you know, I think that I've been very, you've been great.

481
00:44:37,292 --> 00:44:38,652
Me and you have talked many times.

482
00:44:38,732 --> 00:44:41,094
And when I hear a rumor, I call you right away.

483
00:44:41,194 --> 00:44:44,075
And that's why I wanted to bring these out to you publicly.

484
00:44:44,395 --> 00:44:48,898
And I appreciate all of the answers and the time you took to answer those questions.

485
00:44:48,918 --> 00:44:49,978
So I really appreciate it, Tim.

486
00:44:50,018 --> 00:44:50,258
Thanks.

487
00:44:50,759 --> 00:44:51,179
Absolutely.

488
00:44:51,219 --> 00:44:52,800
I'm always available if you guys have questions.

489
00:44:53,080 --> 00:44:53,380
Thank you.

490
00:44:54,418 --> 00:44:54,819
Thank you.

491
00:44:54,839 --> 00:44:56,700
I'm going to recognize Councillor Seng.

492
00:44:57,781 --> 00:44:58,282
Thank you.

493
00:44:58,722 --> 00:45:00,564
Thanks, Sim, for being here with us today.

494
00:45:01,565 --> 00:45:10,012
Before I say anything, I'm very grateful to the staff at DPW for all their work clearing all the snow from this year.

495
00:45:10,153 --> 00:45:12,235
I mean, it was an incredible

496
00:45:13,035 --> 00:45:18,880
amount of snow that I don't think many of us were expecting, and certainly a lot of hard work.

497
00:45:19,300 --> 00:45:41,917
I heard staff on the roads at all times of the day during the storms, and I think a lot of residents, you know, despite what complaints we may have heard, a lot, if not most, if not all of the residents that I talked to, I think, recognized that it was a really tough storm and that people were working really, really hard.

498
00:45:42,676 --> 00:45:53,603
I also want to just thank you for your responsiveness during the storm in terms of the roads that I was sending in, the communications about state roads, helping pass that on to MassDOT.

499
00:45:54,204 --> 00:45:57,266
It was very helpful to residents in the city as well.

500
00:45:59,167 --> 00:46:05,151
I think a lot of the questions I have, there's significant overlap with other councillors who've already asked questions before.

501
00:46:05,171 --> 00:46:10,655
A lot of Councillor Scarfelli's questions, Councillor Lozano's questions about

502
00:46:11,822 --> 00:46:19,445
like public sidewalks and assessing businesses and hospitals and clinics, stuff like that.

503
00:46:19,605 --> 00:46:24,407
I think a lot of people found it difficult to get to their appointments.

504
00:46:25,108 --> 00:46:33,331
And so it's good to know that we'll have more of a plan for the sidewalks for the next year going forward as well.

505
00:46:34,872 --> 00:46:38,233
And I think you've also anticipated some of the questions I had

506
00:46:39,233 --> 00:46:48,478
about equipment that we might need as well, but I guess going through, I just have a few more questions if that's okay with you, Tim.

507
00:46:49,419 --> 00:46:58,204
I'm a bit curious about just the staffing and kind of the need for contractors.

508
00:46:58,224 --> 00:47:03,887
Of course, I think you noted that we're seeing a lot fewer contractors available than in the past.

509
00:47:05,887 --> 00:47:07,168
reasons for that, you know.

510
00:47:08,008 --> 00:47:25,278
But I'm curious about whether there are any, like, there were any capacity gaps that required more contractors than usual besides, like, taking the large volume of snow out of the question, compared to maybe where we were 10 years ago?

511
00:47:25,298 --> 00:47:32,161
Is there kind of fewer staff at DPW that requires us to kind of fill more of a gap than before?

512
00:47:32,181 --> 00:47:35,023
That's a good question.

513
00:47:39,494 --> 00:47:41,355
I should wait for- No, no, please.

514
00:47:42,336 --> 00:47:43,076
I recognize you.

515
00:47:43,577 --> 00:47:43,937
Okay.

516
00:47:44,297 --> 00:47:46,999
So it's a good question.

517
00:47:47,019 --> 00:47:54,523
So just so folks are aware, so the DPW just in general over time, decades, has been getting smaller.

518
00:47:55,264 --> 00:48:01,448
So there was a time, people tell me, I haven't gone and looked at annual reports, but I have looked at some annual reports from back in the day.

519
00:48:02,208 --> 00:48:06,070
People say that we were 120 people, which I wouldn't be surprised.

520
00:48:06,110 --> 00:48:06,590
Right now we're at 70.

521
00:48:06,650 --> 00:48:12,292
So if there was a time that they tell me about, we were double.

522
00:48:12,312 --> 00:48:20,916
I've looked at annual reports from the different time periods, and certainly the DPW has been a lot bigger than it is today.

523
00:48:21,556 --> 00:48:27,259
We, as I think many of you know, we effectively get a cut almost every single year.

524
00:48:27,279 --> 00:48:29,700
And as you can imagine, over time,

525
00:48:30,621 --> 00:48:34,553
That, you know, you just lose kind of one position at a time and we go from 120 to here we are at 70.

526
00:48:40,301 --> 00:48:43,022
As you know, I'm working on sort of right-sizing each division.

527
00:48:43,082 --> 00:48:46,003
I talk about it a little bit almost every time at budget season.

528
00:48:47,543 --> 00:48:53,905
And, you know, highway is better than it was last year, because we got three more positions there.

529
00:48:55,765 --> 00:48:58,926
But it's really a matter of time.

530
00:48:59,386 --> 00:49:06,228
If you doubled the amount of pieces that we had on the road from 50 to 100, then we're going to clear the roads twice as quick.

531
00:49:07,528 --> 00:49:10,010
So that math is pretty simple and it's real.

532
00:49:10,530 --> 00:49:18,355
So when we have 50 or so of our own pieces and then we get 30 or so contractors, we're talking 80 pieces of equipment out of the road.

533
00:49:18,815 --> 00:49:22,998
So that's still less than our peak days of an internal DPW.

534
00:49:24,658 --> 00:49:38,342
So, you know, if we may, if we had 120 people in DBW and highway, you had, you know, 100 plows to their disposal in-house, then we probably don't even need to call any contractors.

535
00:49:39,122 --> 00:49:41,322
But then, of course, you have to support that staff all year round.

536
00:49:42,483 --> 00:49:45,543
So hopefully that kind of sheds a little bit of light on that.

537
00:49:46,624 --> 00:49:50,925
It's not necessarily you look at the amount of snow and the size of the city and say, oh, well, we're going to need 100,

538
00:49:52,110 --> 00:49:59,378
pieces of equipment for that it's more like we have 50, so it's going to take, you know, x amount of hours to clear the streets.

539
00:50:00,019 --> 00:50:07,307
I would say if we had less than, then, you know, I don't know 70 or so 70 would be our 50 plus another 20 contractors.

540
00:50:08,593 --> 00:50:13,915
you know, we're starting to probably get on that border of it's not big enough is not enough.

541
00:50:14,616 --> 00:50:18,177
And we talked about that this year, like what is not enough?

542
00:50:19,318 --> 00:50:21,039
And I don't know the answer to that.

543
00:50:21,119 --> 00:50:27,422
But you know, if we didn't have contractors, we didn't have those 24 contractors come in, and it was just 50 or 54 plows that we have, then

544
00:50:31,063 --> 00:50:39,931
It's just going to take longer and it increases the risk during the storm that an emergency vehicle is not going to be able to get to go where it needs to go.

545
00:50:39,951 --> 00:50:43,955
And then, of course, we all know what happens if that's the case.

546
00:50:44,516 --> 00:50:47,398
So, you know, those are the games we're kind of playing here.

547
00:50:47,879 --> 00:50:48,579
They're very real.

548
00:50:49,901 --> 00:50:51,742
And I think, you know, when

549
00:50:52,843 --> 00:51:03,849
this body is thinking about the size of DPW and future services, then I'm always willing to talk about that.

550
00:51:04,269 --> 00:51:13,874
I've been trying to do a lot of work as city engineer and DPW commissioner to understand what right sizing of a DPW is and what that means and how do you apply it.

551
00:51:14,274 --> 00:51:16,996
And there's lots of good information out there and lots of different opinions.

552
00:51:19,015 --> 00:51:27,500
I mean, I think with this question, right, I mean, I think what the council has been interested in in the last few years is, what is that race face?

553
00:51:27,560 --> 00:51:30,262
And it's a very difficult question to answer.

554
00:51:30,302 --> 00:51:34,725
I'm sure we've had a lot of conversations about it, especially during budget season.

555
00:51:35,085 --> 00:51:41,069
But I mean, as the next budget season is approaching, it's a question I think a lot of us might have in our heads.

556
00:51:41,369 --> 00:51:45,972
And I think on the council generally, we've made some progress with the override, but

557
00:51:46,957 --> 00:52:01,281
still there's, I think, you know, the concern is that the 50 and the 30 are both shrinking, and I think it sounds like we've turned around or starting to turn around when it comes to the 50 component of it.

558
00:52:01,841 --> 00:52:09,163
I know we're just taking a random number for the 50, but that, you know, I think it's something for us to pay attention to as we

559
00:52:10,393 --> 00:52:24,063
budget for future years to make sure that we're keeping the DPW part of the pie kind of there, especially as it seems like maybe the contractor number is getting smaller and smaller.

560
00:52:24,784 --> 00:52:25,965
So thank you for that answer.

561
00:52:28,437 --> 00:52:31,539
I appreciate the answers about equipment.

562
00:52:32,540 --> 00:52:37,804
I'm curious about the snow blower loader attachment that you were talking about.

563
00:52:37,824 --> 00:52:43,809
Of course, it's hard for us to predict what winter's coming up will be like.

564
00:52:47,711 --> 00:52:50,953
there are kind of two different questions I'm interested in.

565
00:52:50,973 --> 00:53:03,182
The first one being, is this a formal budget request that's been made to the mayor to incorporate either in this budget or through a capital fund?

566
00:53:04,103 --> 00:53:07,926
Or is this just kind of an idea that we're talking about right now?

567
00:53:08,026 --> 00:53:10,248
Like, what stage are we at in that?

568
00:53:11,508 --> 00:53:15,912
And then on top of that, let's say it doesn't really snow this

569
00:53:16,847 --> 00:53:18,868
this much in the next two winters.

570
00:53:19,068 --> 00:53:26,030
But it's a piece of equipment we really could use in an inventory.

571
00:53:26,050 --> 00:53:30,992
Is it a piece of equipment that deteriorates even when it's not being used?

572
00:53:31,052 --> 00:53:34,353
Or is it the use of it that really makes it deteriorate?

573
00:53:35,774 --> 00:53:36,394
Good question.

574
00:53:36,734 --> 00:53:37,794
So I'll go in reverse.

575
00:53:38,755 --> 00:53:41,515
All equipment just starts deteriorating immediately when you buy it.

576
00:53:42,076 --> 00:53:44,156
And if it just sits around, it's

577
00:53:46,715 --> 00:53:53,700
It has diesel fluid in it that can crystallize if it sits around too long.

578
00:53:54,180 --> 00:53:56,842
So we would need to exercise it, turn it on every now and then.

579
00:53:57,342 --> 00:54:01,024
Anybody who owns a diesel truck and doesn't drive it all that much, I think, knows that.

580
00:54:01,625 --> 00:54:03,486
You got to turn it on and run it every now and then.

581
00:54:04,126 --> 00:54:05,907
So we would need to do that.

582
00:54:06,728 --> 00:54:08,389
So there's some responsibility there.

583
00:54:09,309 --> 00:54:14,573
So there's a risk that it sits around, doesn't get used, and all of a sudden, we go to try to start it up one year, and it doesn't work.

584
00:54:16,466 --> 00:54:24,932
So then that's really the concern and also the capital cost, because we're talking about a piece of machinery that's well over six figures.

585
00:54:25,733 --> 00:54:30,837
And is that the right purchase for this climate and this weather?

586
00:54:30,857 --> 00:54:36,241
And I have an opinion on that, but I think it might differ from others' opinions.

587
00:54:37,021 --> 00:54:41,445
It would be a very handy piece of equipment, and I would like to have one.

588
00:54:42,525 --> 00:54:47,691
And we'd have to take the proper precautions and treat it as an investment.

589
00:54:47,972 --> 00:54:53,037
And we'd have to all understand that it may not get used for multiple years in a row.

590
00:54:55,020 --> 00:54:59,024
I mean, it definitely makes sense that this is like, you can't foresee it, right?

591
00:54:59,184 --> 00:55:00,406
But once you need it, you need it.

592
00:55:02,961 --> 00:55:17,395
I'm curious, I guess, I guess there's still the component of the question about whether the formal asks has been made, but I'm also curious, generally, our equipment kind of equipment inventory compares to the municipalities around us would like.

593
00:55:18,491 --> 00:55:25,973
maybe comparing it by mileage or the mileage that we have to plow as a city or sidewalk equipment at that as well.

594
00:55:26,173 --> 00:55:44,379
I know a few residents have kind of complained about sidewalks, snow removal, which we've kind of addressed at this point already, but I'm curious how the number of pieces of equipment that we have for that compares to, say, the municipalities around us.

595
00:55:45,388 --> 00:55:45,588
Sure.

596
00:55:45,968 --> 00:55:46,368
Yeah, you're right.

597
00:55:46,388 --> 00:55:47,148
I didn't answer your question.

598
00:55:47,309 --> 00:55:50,449
So we do have the Snowblower attachment on the CIP.

599
00:55:50,849 --> 00:55:58,491
It's been on there for a number of years, but we keep pushing it back because it's a large purchase that isn't necessarily an immediate need.

600
00:55:58,551 --> 00:56:00,032
It's more of a nice to have.

601
00:56:00,792 --> 00:56:11,035
So anyway, and then as far as surrounding communities and what they have, I don't actually know what they have specifically for numbers, but you know,

602
00:56:12,355 --> 00:56:16,238
We have the capacity really to operate two sidewalk machines.

603
00:56:17,338 --> 00:56:18,679
So that's what we have.

604
00:56:18,719 --> 00:56:22,941
So we actually have the amount of machines for the size of our workforce.

605
00:56:24,202 --> 00:56:29,605
And then I can talk about one other thing, the right sizing of highway.

606
00:56:29,705 --> 00:56:38,270
So I did a calculation before the override to compare the size of our highway division to other highway divisions.

607
00:56:41,407 --> 00:56:45,249
as far as number of people compared to road miles managed.

608
00:56:46,290 --> 00:56:50,232
And we were on the lower side of most of it.

609
00:56:51,652 --> 00:56:54,614
But the biggest takeaway was that there's a huge disparity.

610
00:56:55,014 --> 00:57:04,519
The Brooklines and Cambridges of Massachusetts have larger highway divisions, more people to take care of their roads, but not necessarily more roads than us.

611
00:57:05,499 --> 00:57:10,562
And we have less I think I was like point one per road miles point one people per road mile.

612
00:57:11,202 --> 00:57:13,444
And, you know, other places were point two.

613
00:57:13,464 --> 00:57:22,809
I ended up being that we should be somewhere in the middle I don't know still what that right number is and I'm not sure anybody knows what the right number is.

614
00:57:24,450 --> 00:57:28,092
But I think it should be a little bit higher than what it currently is.

615
00:57:28,373 --> 00:57:32,095
So, you know, we had 50, we're just talking winter, right?

616
00:57:32,155 --> 00:57:49,967
So in the context of winter, 50 plows out there that are in-house plows, if that was 70, like we talked about, which would be 20 more pieces of equipment, 20 more people, then we're starting to skirt the line of, well, do we even need contractors for most storms?

617
00:57:50,513 --> 00:57:56,976
You know, so that, to me, feels like more of an appropriate size if you were to just look at winter.

618
00:57:58,497 --> 00:58:04,159
Because contracting, in all aspects of public works, contracting is usually more money at the end of the day than to do it in-house.

619
00:58:04,440 --> 00:58:08,782
But you have to pick and choose what gets done in-house and what is done by a contractor.

620
00:58:09,222 --> 00:58:11,123
So anyway, hopefully that sheds some light.

621
00:58:12,764 --> 00:58:14,184
No, it definitely does.

622
00:58:16,496 --> 00:58:22,502
I was going to ask, actually, how do we choose what gets done in-house versus what gets done by a contractor?

623
00:58:24,243 --> 00:58:26,325
It has a lot to do with regularity.

624
00:58:26,726 --> 00:58:27,847
That's one of the variables.

625
00:58:27,887 --> 00:58:34,713
So if it's something that we're going to do every week or every month, then you start to say, well, maybe that should be in-house.

626
00:58:35,154 --> 00:58:36,235
A lot of that already is in-house.

627
00:58:36,797 --> 00:58:45,385
So like, for example, one of the things that we had to decide in-house or contractor somewhat recently is how to deal with sidewalk repairs.

628
00:58:45,425 --> 00:58:47,407
We have thousands of sidewalk repair requests.

629
00:58:47,847 --> 00:58:52,131
We have to prioritize and figure what we're going to do with them.

630
00:58:52,691 --> 00:58:59,677
If they're categorized as that street's going to receive a capital improvement, then highway's not going to go do spot repairs there.

631
00:59:00,939 --> 00:59:07,365
Highway is going to do spot repairs that are not going to be problematic from a mobilization standpoint.

632
00:59:08,045 --> 00:59:16,093
A good example is if we hire a contractor to spot repairs on sidewalks, which we have in previous years, you're basically paying a contractor to move their equipment from one place to another.

633
00:59:17,642 --> 00:59:19,264
So, you know, that's not a good use of money.

634
00:59:19,824 --> 00:59:27,830
So that would be something that you say, well, we should, we need to do that in-house because why are we spending 80 cents on the dollar on moving a machine to another spot in the city?

635
00:59:28,611 --> 00:59:32,514
So that's just an example, one example of how you make the determination.

636
00:59:32,534 --> 00:59:37,417
Is that going to be in-house or is that going to be, you know, outhouse, contractor?

637
00:59:37,998 --> 00:59:38,799
There are more.

638
00:59:39,659 --> 00:59:44,563
I guess in the, in the context of winter storms, is there a difference between like what,

639
00:59:45,214 --> 00:59:50,716
what they're doing on the road or not really?

640
00:59:50,776 --> 00:59:51,016
No.

641
00:59:51,296 --> 00:59:53,217
It's written down in our contract, so three inches.

642
00:59:53,797 --> 01:00:00,880
If the forecast is for three inches and above, then we set a contractor call in time, and that's when the contractors come in.

643
01:00:00,980 --> 01:00:03,101
It's after DPW all in.

644
01:00:03,921 --> 01:00:10,603
We do highway first, and that's where you see Salters out, and then it's DPW all in, so all members of DPW come in.

645
01:00:11,164 --> 01:00:14,485
Then usually a couple hours after that is when contractors come in.

646
01:00:14,985 --> 01:00:22,228
so that by that time all the foremen have their route assignments worked out, how many contractors they need, etc.

647
01:00:23,388 --> 01:00:23,708
Got it.

648
01:00:24,828 --> 01:00:26,269
Thanks for that.

649
01:00:28,090 --> 01:00:37,933
